   <mods:abstract>Thanks for the $26,000 paid to Mr. Cabarrus on order of Mr. Gardoqui. As
            for the rest of the bills drawn on Jay by Congress, since it is such a small sum
            Cabarrus offered to pay it on the assurance that the Spanish king repays him within a
            year. If not, the credit of Congress will be ruined. Upset by KingÆs displeasure at
            CongressÆ silence concerning propositions on shipbuilding in New England. Congress had
            postponed discussion in expectation of GardoquiÆs arrival in America. Can assure the
            king in the name of Congress of strong desire to accommodate Spanish wishes, and hopes
            future military success will bring Americans closer to realizing their goals. Reminds
            him that Mississippi proposals demonstrate CongressÆ willingness to oblige the Spanish
            king and had hoped for subsequent proof of his goodwill. Completely out of money and
            unable to procure it from the French ambassador.</mods:abstract>
